is majority of combined voting power (Class A + Class B voting together)\n\n---\n\n## Conversion Mechanics\n\n- **Voluntary:** Each Class B share is convertible at any time at the holder\'s option into one share of Class A\n- **Automatic:** Each Class B share converts automatically into one share of Class A upon any **Transfer** (whether or not for value), except for **Permitted Transfers** (inter-family transfers and transfers to certain qualifying entities)\n- **Effect of conversion:** Over time, conversion of Class B to Class A increases the relative voting power of those Class B holders who retain their shares\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nThe structure creates a **permanent dual-mechanism** where Class B shareholders — effectively Elon Musk — control a guaranteed **majority of the board** through their separate class vote, while also controlling all remaining board seats and every general corporate matter through their dominant combined voting power derived from the **10:1 vote premium**. This concentration of power exists *"for so long as any shares of Class B common stock remain outstanding"* and cannot be diluted by public Class A shareholders.',
