 Floor vs. a Mathematical Premium\n\n| Feature | Conventional 10:1 Dual-Class | SpaceX Dual-Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| **How control is maintained** | Entirely through arithmetic: the 10:1 vote premium must mathematically produce a majority of total voting power | Two layers: (1) a **structural guarantee** of 51% of board seats via the separate class vote, regardless of economics; (2) the 10:1 vote premium for remaining seats and general matters |\n| **What happens if controlling class\'s economic interest erodes** | If Class B\'s share count declines (through dilution or conversion) such that their 10× votes fall below 50% of total voting power, they lose control of *all* directors | Class B holders **always** elect 51% of the board as long as *any* Class B shares exist, even if they represent a trivial fraction of total economic interest |\n| **Vulnerability to dilution** | The 10:1 premium is mathematically erodable; sufficient new Class A issuance can tip combined voting power | The separate class vote is **immune to dilution**; it is a binary structural right, not a function of share proportions |\n\n**Illustrative example:** Suppose Class B shareholders hold only 5% of total shares outstanding, with Class A holding 95%. In a conventional 10:1 structure, Class B\'s combined voting power would be:\n- (5 × 10) / (5 × 10 + 95 × 1) = 50/145 = **34.5%** — Class B loses board control entirely.\n\nUnder SpaceX\'s structure, Class B would **still elect 51% of the board** (5 of 8 directors) through the separate class vote, despite holding only 34.5% of combined voting power and just 5% of economic interest.\n\n#### B. The Contested-Director Ceiling Is Hard-Capped at 49%\n\nIn a conventional dual-class structure, if Class A shareholders collectively acquire enough economic interest to overcome the 10:1 premium in combined voting, they can theoretically elect *all* directors.\n\nUnder SpaceX\'s charter, **Class A shareholders can never elect more than 49% of directors** (rounded down), regardless of how many shares they hold. With an 8-member board, that means at most 3 seats. The remaining 5 are structurally reserved for Class B.\n\nThis is not a practical disadvantage that can be overcome with capital—it is a **charter-level structural constraint** that persists until the last Class B share converts.\n\n#### C. The 10:1 Premium Operates Only Within a Constrained Arena\n\nIn a conventional structure, the 10:1 premium operates across 100% of board seats and 100% of general matters. In SpaceX\'s structure, the 10:1 premium only determines outcomes for:\n- The ~49% of board seats elected by combined vote (3 of 8 initially)\n- All general shareholder matters (mergers, charter amendments not affecting Class B, etc.)\n\nFor the ~51% of board seats, the 10:1 premium is irrelevant—those seats are determined solely by the separate class vote.\n\n---\n\n### III. Specific Implication for a Class A Shareholder\'s Ability to Influence Board Composition\n\nEven if Class A shareholders collectively hold a **majority of economic interest** (say, 60%, 70%, or even 95% of shares outstanding), their ability to influence board composition is constrained in the following ways:\n\n**1. Permanent exclusion from 51% of board seats:**\nClass A shareholders have **zero** ability to nominate, elect, vote for, or remove Class B Directors. With the initial 8-member board, that means 5 of 8 seats (62.5%) are entirely beyond Class A\'s reach. This right is not a function of share ownership—it is a structural charter entitlement reserved exclusively for Class B holders.\n\n**2. Severely constrained influence over the remaining ~49% of seats:**\nFor Common Stock Director seats (3 of 8 initially), Class A and Class B vote together. But Class B shares carry 10 votes each. Even if Class A shareholders held, hypothetically, 91% of shares (vs. 9% Class B), Class B\'s combined voting power would be:\n- (9 × 10) / (9 × 10 + 91 × 1) = 90/181 = **49.7%**\n\nClass A, despite holding 91% of economic interest, would hold barely 50.3% of combined voting power—enough for a razor-thin majority on just 3 seats. At any Class B economic interest above ~9.1%, the 10:1 premium alone gives Class B majority combined voting power, meaning Class B controls *all* seats.\n\n**3. In practice, with disclosed ownership levels, Class A has effectively no influence:**\nPre-offering, Elon Musk held 5,569,053,075 Class B shares (carrying ~55.7 billion votes) and 849,494,440 Class A shares, representing ~88.9% of combined voting power. At these levels, Class B holders control both the separate-class vote (5 seats) and the combined vote (3 seats), giving them control of the **entire** board through both mechanisms simultaneously.\n\n**4. No cumulative or proxy access relief:**\nThe filing does not disclose cumulative voting, proxy access, or any other mechanism that would allow minority Class A shareholders to concentrate votes on a subset of candidates. For the 3 Common Stock Director seats, Class B\'s vote weight in the combined election will typically determine the outcome.\n\n---\n\n### IV. Summary Comparison Table\n\n| Dimension | Conventional 10:1 Dual-Class | SpaceX Dual-Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Director election method** | All directors elected by combined vote with 10:1 premium | 51% by Class B separate class vote; ~49% by combined vote |\n| **Controlling class needs to hold** | Enough shares so that (shares × 10) > 50% of total voting power | Any non-zero number of Class B shares for 51% of board; voting-power majority for remaining seats |\n| **Can economic majority by Class A overcome control?** | Yes, if Class A\'s share count overwhelms the 10:1 premium | **No**—51% of board is structurally locked for Class B regardless of economics |\n| **Maximum board seats Class A can influence** | 100% (if they achieve voting-power majority) | ~49% (hard ceiling) |\n| **Vulnerability to dilution** | Mathematically erodable | Class B Director seats are dilution-proof |\n| **Persistence** | Ends when 10:1 premium is insufficient | Ends only when the last Class B share converts |\n\n### V. Bottom Line\n\nSpaceX\'s dual-mechanism structure is **strictly more protective of founder control** than a conventional 10:1 dual-class arrangement. The conventional structure relies solely on arithmetic—a premium that can, in theory, be diluted away. SpaceX\'s structure layers a **non-arithmetic, structural guarantee** (the separate class vote for 51% of directors) on top of the arithmetic premium. The practical implication is that a Class A shareholder—even one representing a consortium holding a majority of economic interest—cannot influence the election of a majority of the board and faces prohibitive disadvantages in contesting even the minority of seats technically open to combined voting. The Class B separate-class veto is absolute and binary: it exists or it does not, and as long as any Class B shares remain outstanding, it does.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n1. SpaceX S-1 Filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm — "Description of Capital Stock" section; "Management — Directors and Executive Officers" section; "Security Ownership of Certain Beneficial Owners and Management" section.',
